            "id": "6b18755603cb4734a29c2",
            "questionText": "In a photoelectric effect experiment, a metal surface is illuminated with light of two different wavelengths. The first wavelength, $!$\\lambda_1 = 300 \\text{ nm}$!$, results in a stopping potential of $!$1.5 \\text{ V}$!$. When the wavelength is changed to $!$\\lambda_2 = 200 \\text{ nm}$!$, the stopping potential increases to $!$3.0 \\text{ V}$!$. Determine the work function $!$\\phi$!$ of the metal in electron volts ($!$\\text{eV}$!$). Use $!$h = 6.626 \\times 10^{-34} \\text{ Js}$!$ and $!$c = 3 \\times 10^8 \\text{ m/s}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "1205f97706d44fa180929",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the relation that connects the speed of light, frequency, and wavelength. Select the correct formula that relates these quantities.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "af40d0c0-79b8-4f61-ae04-181c33113b03"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$c = f \\lambda$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$c = \\frac{f}{\\lambda}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f = c \\lambda$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "e2769c777fa34d51b1517",
                    "stepText": "Great. Now, convert the first wavelength $!$\\lambda_1 = 300\\;nm$!$ into meters before using it in any calculations. What is $\\lambda_1$ in meters?",
