            "id": "eacc67e9abb24211bb323",
            "questionText": "An electron microscope uses electrons accelerated through a potential difference to image a sample. To achieve a resolution capable of resolving features of approximately $!$0.05 \\text{ nm}$!$, what accelerating voltage ($!$V$!$) is required? Assume the electron is non-relativistic, and use the following constants: electron mass $!$m = 9.11 \\times 10^{-31} \\text{ kg}$!$, elementary charge $!$q = 1.602 \\times 10^{-19} \\text{ C}$!$, and Planck's constant $!$h = 6.626 \\times 10^{-34} \\text{ Js}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "06d57aff65724c36ad7a7",
                    "stepText": "Let's begin by identifying the appropriate relation that connects the electron's wavelength to its accelerating voltage. Recall that for electrons, the de Broglie wavelength can be expressed in terms of the accelerating voltage. Choose the option that correctly represents this relation.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2fc1331f-b464-447e-aaa9-e1806d7e9191",
                        "6ebe6c0d-c162-454d-9895-d18bb1afb5b9"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = \\frac{h}{\\sqrt{2mqV}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = \\frac{h}{2mqV}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$\\lambda = \\frac{h\\sqrt{2mqV}}{}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "ac65d66195c545af8f1c0",
                    "stepText": "Great. Now, rearrange the chosen equation to solve for the accelerating voltage $!$V$!$. Identify the correct re-arranged form where $!$V$!$ is isolated.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2fc1331f-b464-447e-aaa9-e1806d7e9191"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$V = \\frac{h^2}{2mq\\lambda^2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$V = \\frac{2mq\\lambda^2}{h^2}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$V = \\frac{h}{2mq\\lambda}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "30097976ada74723adccb",
                    "stepText": "Now, convert the resolution requirement into the proper units and calculate its square. Given that the required resolution is $!$0.05 \\text{ nm}$!$, first express it in meters, then determine $!$\\lambda^2$ for use in the equation.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
